Coexpression_evigene_complete

Fernando

August 31, 2018

This document contains the code and results from a clustering analyisis on the gene expression data for the RNA-seq experiment ZCWD2018 to identify coexpressed genes across development in males and females.

# load data ................................................................................

edata    <- read.table('evigene_24865_transcript_expression.txt', header = TRUE, row.names = 1 )
pdata    <- read.table('pheno_data.txt', header = TRUE, row.names = 1 )

## Remove failed libraries and filter low expressed genes ..................................

failed <- c('ZWD103', 'ZWD204', 'ZWD110','ZWD206', 'ZWD557', 'ZWD125', 'ZWD101', 'ZWD109', 'ZWD208', 'ZWD207','ZWD209','ZWD212','ZWD217', 'HEAD', 'THORAX', 'ZWD124')

edata      <- edata[ , !names(edata) %in% failed ]
edata_cpm  <- cpm(edata)
treshold   <- edata_cpm > 0.3
edata      <- edata[rowSums(treshold) > 1,]
edata      <- edata[rowSums(edata) > 100,]

# Update pdata and Rearange factors .................................................................

pdata        <- pdata[row.names(pdata) %in% colnames(edata),]
pdata        <- pdata[order(pdata$group, pdata$sex),]
pdata$group  <- factor(pdata$group, levels = unique(pdata$group))
pdata$instar <- factor(pdata$instar, levels = unique(pdata$instar))
pdata$sample <- factor(row.names(pdata), levels = row.names(pdata))

edata <- ArrangeEdata(edata,pdata)
edata <- round(edata)

The cluster analyisis will be performed using standarized read counts. For that, the standarization methods used by DESeq will be used.

# Pack data into a DESeq object  and normalize .............................................

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = as.matrix(edata),
                              colData   = pdata,
                              design    = ~ sex)
## converting counts to integer mode
factor_size <- estimateSizeFactors(dds)
edata_norm  <- as.data.frame(counts(factor_size, normalized = TRUE))

# Split normalized data by sex and remove low expresed genes ...............................

edata_f <- edata_norm[ ,pdata$sex == 'F' ]
edata_f <- edata_f[ rowSums(edata_f) > 50, ]
pdata_f <- pdata[ pdata$sex == 'F', ]

edata_m <- edata_norm[ ,pdata$sex == 'M' ]
edata_m <- edata_m[ rowSums(edata_m) > 50, ]
pdata_m <- pdata[ pdata$sex == 'M', ]

Cluster analysis

Transcripts will be clustered based on the similarities on their expression profiles across development separatly in males and females. The clustering will be performed using MBCluster.seq package with clusters transcripts using a negative bionomial distribution model for RNA-seq read counts.

# Clustering of female gene expression ...................................................................................

clusters_f <- cluster_transcripts_MBC(edata_f, pdata_f)
## [1] "--->>>> iteration stops after 30 steps"
saveRDS(clusters_f, './output/clusters_f.rds')
clusters_f <- readRDS('./output/clusters_f.rds')

clusters_m <- cluster_transcripts_MBC(edata_m, pdata_m)
## [1] "--->>>> iteration stops after 30 steps"
saveRDS(clusters_m, './output/clusters_m.rds')
clusters_m <- readRDS('./output/clusters_m.rds')

The graphs below shows a heatmap of standarized expression values with a dendrogram that reflects the distance between clusters in females followed by the expression profiles of females clusters

for (i in c(1:20)) {
    plot_cluster(edata_f, pdata_f, clusters_f$probabilities, i, col = 2)
}

The graphs below shows the correspondent patterns for males

for (i in c(1:20)) {
    plot_cluster(edata_m, pdata_m, clusters_m$probabilities, i, col = 1)
}
